\section{Extending lead-free hybrid photovoltaic materials to new structures: thiazolium, aminothiazolium and imidazolium iodobismuthatesi}
\begin{abstract}
Tianyue Li, (ID $\ddagger^{a}$ Qifei Wang, $\uplus^{b}$ Gary S. Nichol, (iD ${ }^{a}$ Carole A. Morrison, (iD ${ }^{a}$ Hongwei Han, id ${ }^{b}$ Yue Hu id *b and Neil Robertson iD *a 
 We report on the synthesis, crystal structures, optoelectronic properties and solar cell device studies of three novel organic-inorganic iodobismuthates - $\left[\mathrm{C}_{3} \mathrm{H}_{4} \mathrm{NSS}_{3}\left[\left.\mathrm{Bi}_{2}\right|_{9}\right] \quad\left([\mathrm{TH}]_{3}\left[\mathrm{Bi}_{2} \mathrm{l}_{9}\right]\right), \quad\left[\mathrm{C}_{3} \mathrm{H}_{4} \mathrm{~N}_{2}\right]_{3}\left[\left.\mathrm{Bi}_{2}\right|_{9}\right]\right.$ ([IM $]_{3}\left[\mathbf{B i}_{2} \mathbf{l}_{9}\right]$ ) and $\left[\mathrm{C}_{3} \mathrm{H}_{5} \mathrm{~N}_{2} \mathrm{~S}\right]\left[\mathrm{Bil}_{4}\right]\left([\mathrm{AT}]\left[\mathrm{Bil}_{4}\right]\right)$ as lead-free light harvesters. $[\mathbf{T H}]_{3}\left[\mathrm{Bi}_{2} \mathbf{I}_{\mathbf{9}}\right]$ and $\left[\mathrm{MM}_{3}\left[\mathrm{Bi}_{2} \mathbf{l}_{\mathbf{9}}\right]\right.$ show zero-dimensional structures, whereas a one-dimensional edge-sharing chain structure of Bil ${ }_{6}$-octahedra was observed in $[\mathrm{AT}]\left[\mathrm{Bil}_{4}\right]$, with interchain short $|\ldots|$ contacts also giving rise to the possibility of threedimensional charge transport ability. Accordingly, greater energy dispersion in the band structure of [AT][Bil $\left.{ }_{4}\right]$ can be observed, and less contribution from the organic moities at the conduction band minimum in $[\mathrm{AT}]\left[\mathrm{Bil}_{4}\right]$ than $\left[\mathrm{TH}_{3}\left[\mathrm{Bi}_{2} \mathbf{l}_{9}\right]\right.$ have been confirmed by density functional theory calculations. Moreover, bandgap values are redshifted from $2.08 \mathrm{eV}$ for $[\mathbf{T H}]_{3}\left[\mathbf{B i}_{2} \mathbf{I}_{9}\right]$ and $2.00$ eV for $[\mathbf{I M}]_{3}\left[\mathbf{B i}_{2} \mathbf{I}_{9}\right]$ to $1.78$ eV for [AT][Bil ${ }_{4}$ ], determined by UV-Vis reflectance spectroscopy. Power conversion efficiency of $0.47 \%$ 
 ![](http://10.128.0.40/eqn-images/2023_09_22_5237e17b3b341fecc9d9g-1_1244_1283_593_1918.jpg) cell, with relatively good reproducibility. We also note the observation of a capacitance effect for the first time in a photovoltaic device with bismuth-based solar absorber, which may be related to the mesoporous carbon counter-electrode.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Photovoltaic (PV) devices based on hybrid lead halide perovskite materials have been extensively studied with merits including low cost, ${ }^{1}$ high absorption coefficient, ${ }^{2}$ small exciton binding energy, ${ }^{3,4}$ long charge carrier diffusion length ${ }^{5,6}$ and commercial scalability. ${ }^{7,8}$ In the last few years, the power conversion efficiency (PCE) of lead perovskite solar cells soared from 3.9\% (ref. 9) in 2013 to over $22 \%$ today, ${ }^{10}$ as well as much increased stability under humidity and oxygen. ${ }^{11-14}$ In addition, lead-halide perovskites have also been studied in

